Richardson Maturity Model (Simple Explanation)

It’s a way to measure how “RESTful” your API is. There are four levels (0–3). The higher the
level, the better your API follows REST rules.

Level 0: One Endpoint, One Method

(i)   You have just one URL for everything.
(ii)  You use only POST (or GET).
(iii) You send a big request with an “action” field telling the server what to do.

Example:
POST /api
{ "action": "getUser", "userId": 123 }

Why it’s not good:

(i) Doesn’t use HTTP features.
(ii) Hard to understand and maintain.

Level 1: Resources

(i) You create URLs for different things (resources), like /users or /products.
(ii) But you still use only POST for all actions.

Example:
POST /users
{ "action": "create", "name": "Alice" }

Better, but:

Still not using HTTP methods properly.

Level 2: HTTP Methods

You use different HTTP methods for different actions:

a.GET for getting data
b.POST for creating
c.PUT for updating
d.DELETE for deleting
URLs represent resources.

Example:
GET /users/123 (Get user 123)
POST /users (Create a user)
PUT /users/123 (Update user 123)
DELETE /users/123 (Delete user 123)

Why it’s good:

(i) Uses HTTP as it was meant to be used.
(ii) Easier for others to understand and use.

Level 3: Hypermedia (HATEOAS)

(i) Your API responses include links to other actions.
(ii) Clients can discover what they can do next by following links in the response.

Example:
When you get a user, the response includes links to update or delete that user:

{
  "id": 123,
  "name": "Alice",
  "links": [
    { "rel": "self", "href": "/users/123" },
    { "rel": "update", "href": "/users/123" },
    { "rel": "delete", "href": "/users/123" }
  ]
}

Why it’s best:

(i) Clients don’t need to know all URLs ahead of time.
(ii) Makes your API flexible and easy to use.

Why Should You Care?
a. Level 2 is what most good APIs use. It’s standard, easy, and powerful.
b. Level 3 is even better, but not always needed for simple APIs.
c. Higher levels make your API easier to use, more reliable, and more compatible with web
tools.


Interview Tip
If asked, explain:

Level 0: One endpoint, one method, action in request.
Level 1: Multiple endpoints for resources, but still one method.
Level 2: Multiple endpoints, proper HTTP methods.
Level 3: Responses include links to other actions (hypermedia).